## 🐛 Bug Report

<!-- A clear and concise description of what the bug is. -->
Setting alignment to a cell or column will affect other cells

Lib version: 4.3.0

## Steps To Reproduce

<!-- The exact steps required to reproduce the issue, ideally with a code example -->

```ExpressJS
let rotateCol = 'D'
const wb = new ExcelJS.Workbook();
let file = Buffer.from(body.excelBase64, 'base64');
await wb.xlsx.load(file);

// 1. by looping each column => the result it will rotate all cell's text to 90 degress
wb.eachSheet(function (worksheet, sheetId) {
worksheet.columns.forEach(col => {
  if (col.letter == rotateCol) {
    col.style.alignment.textRotation = 90;
  }
})
})

// 2. by looping each row and getting specific cell => the result it will rotate all cell's text to 90 degress
wb.eachSheet(function (worksheet, sheetId) {
  worksheet.eachRow(function(row, rowNum) {
      worksheet.getCell(rotateCol + rowNum).alignment.textRotation == 90;
      // worksheet.getCell(rotateCol + rowNum)model.style.alignment.textRotation == 90; // doesn't work either
  })
})


// 3. By looping rows and cells
wb.eachSheet(function (worksheet, sheetId) {
 let rowCount = worksheet.rowCount;
 let columnCount = worksheet.columnCount;
  for (let i = 1; i <= rowCount; i++) {
     let row = worksheet.getRow(i);
     for (let j = 1; j <= columnCount; j++) {
        if (row._cells._address[0] == rotateCol) {
           row._cells.alignment.textRotation = 90;
           break; // continue to next row
        }
     }
  }
})
```

## The expected behaviour:

The result that I expected was only the texts of "column D" will rotate but the result that I got is all the texts in all columns also rotate.


## Possible solution (optional, but very helpful):
It seems that the alignment is shared to cells, rows, and column.

I tried debugging the 3rd attempt
```javascript
wb.eachSheet(function (worksheet, sheetId) {
 let rowCount = worksheet.rowCount;
 let columnCount = worksheet.columnCount;
  for (let i = 1; i <= rowCount; i++) {
     let row = worksheet.getRow(i);
     for (let j = 1; j <= columnCount; j++) {
        if (row._cells._address[0] == rotateCol) {
           row._cells.alignment.textRotation = 90;               // => after this line executes, all the cells in that row will also have textRotation alignment
           break; // continue to next row
        }
     }
  }
})
```

I hope somebody have some solution or tips.
Thank you very much
